0.body: Octocat aims to be the GitHub API library for Rust. It was created due to a lack of well-maintained alternatives.
0.title: Octocat

1.body:
There are two modes of operation for Octocat. The first (and most common) one is as a webhook event listener: Essentially, the event listener passes payloads to the user, who then responds with a Command that can either contain nothing or a number of futures. The Command is executed as soon as the event loop is free, and the user recieves the result in the form of a Message (an enum which they define). ┌────────────────┐ ┌────────┐
┌──────────────┐ ┌─────┐ ┌─────────────┐◄─┤Result (Message)├──┤ │
│Event Listener├──┤Event├──►│Event Handler│ └────────────────┘ │Executor│
└──────────────┘ └─────┘ └───┬─────────┴─┐ ┌►│ │ │ ▲ └──────────────────┘ └────────┘ │ │ │ ┌───┴───┐ │ │Command│ │ └───┬───┘ ▼ │ ┌───────┴┐ │ User │ └────────┘ The second is as a glorified HTTP client wrapper.

11.body: All builders in Octocat follow a similar pattern. Each one implements the Builder trait, and contains setters for each of its fields, nested or not. ⚠️ Builders and methods are currently limited in their variety. This will change with time, however it may take a while for work to resume.
11.title: Understanding Builders

12.title: The Builder trait

13.body:
Commenting on a commit. let res = CommitCommentBuilder::new() .owner("octocat-rs") .repo("octocat-rs") .sha("fcc8348f8286d05976090a9086d64eefb90e3f8b") .body("Some text here") .execute(&DefaultRequest::new("TOKEN")) .await .unwrap(); // Prints the URL at which you can find the comment you've just made.
dbg!(res.html_url); Reacting to a commit comment. let _ = CommentReactionBuilder::new() .owner("octocat-rs") .repo("octocat-rs") .comment_id(67534661) .reaction(Reaction::Rocket) .execute(&DefaultRequest::new("TOKEN")) .await .unwrap(); // Comment you just reacted to: https://github.com/octocat-rs/octocat-rs/commit/40919cbf40530cf15a002d701a1a1bd6a6006105#commitcomment-67534661
